hopobject.body: Could I borrow your phone, please? olcso kamagra elad Wealthier Americans are more likely to have mercury and arsenic in their systems, which the authors said may be attributable to fish and shellfish consumption, though dental fillings may also have led to higher mercury levels. They also found that richer people tend to have higher levels of caesium and thallium, which are associated with home-grown produce. They also have higher levels of PFCs, compounds people might pick up via waterproof fabrics, as well as fresh meat, fish, and other fresh vegetables. Higher-income people, the researchers noted, are more likely to both grow produce and eat those foods. In addition, wealthier people had higher levels of a toxin called BP3 that is found in sunscreens.
